The previous period had left the clock at 7:57 p.m., already well past the safe hours of a healthy democracy. In Week 26 it advanced by 0.7 minutes to 7:58 p.m. The movement came from a cluster of structural shifts. Schedule G and mass purges pushed the civil service further under political control. Immigration enforcement became a laboratory for rule by exception, where due process and privacy were treated as optional. Surveillance expanded downward onto ordinary people even as transparency narrowed upward around elite wrongdoing. Congress, instead of acting as a brake, largely ratified this direction by cutting public media and foreign aid, tolerating partisan maps, and blocking disclosure in the Epstein affair. Courts sent mixed signals, but the most consequential rulings and appointments favored executive freedom and entrenched power. The net effect was to deepen traits the Clock tracks as late-hour risks: law as weapon, stratified citizenship, unchecked executive authority, and information systems that serve power rather than the public.\
