The most far-reaching development of the week was the formal politicization of the federal workforce. On July 17, Trump signed an order creating Schedule G in the excepted service, a new classification for \'93policy-making or policy-advocating\'94 roles that could be filled and emptied at presidential will. The order was framed as a way to \'93improve operations\'94 at the Department of Veterans Affairs, but its reach extended across agencies. In practice, it meant that thousands of positions once shielded by merit rules could now be treated as political spoils. This did not just change who held those jobs; it changed what those jobs were for. A civil servant who knows she can be fired for crossing a political line will read the law differently. Fear becomes part of the job description.\
