Schedule G landed in a landscape already being cleared of independent voices. At the State Department, more than 1,300 employees were laid off and the Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor was closed, removing a long-standing center of rights advocacy from U.S. diplomacy. At the Department of Education, a reduction in force that would cut nearly half the workforce had been blocked by a lower court, but the Supreme Court stepped in with an emergency stay, allowing the layoffs to proceed. The Court\'92s 6\'963 decision did more than greenlight a single downsizing; it signaled that statutory limits on executive personnel moves could be brushed aside when they interfered with presidential plans. At the Justice Department, Attorney General Pam Bondi fired Joseph Tirrell, the head of the ethics office, and more than twenty other career lawyers, while nearly two-thirds of the unit tasked with defending Trump policies resigned rather than continue work they believed aimed at dismantling constitutional governance. The National Institutes of Health prepared to dismiss scientists from advisory panels and replace them with politically aligned figures. These moves shifted the civil service trait on the Democracy Clock. Neutral administration gave way to a workforce selected and retained for loyalty, not law.\
