The justice system itself was pulled further into this orbit. Bondi\'92s DOJ dropped charges against a Utah doctor who had destroyed COVID vaccines and issued fake cards, recasting him as a provider of \'93choice\'94 rather than a fraud defendant. The department fired Maurene Comey, a career prosecutor who had worked on the Epstein and Ghislaine Maxwell cases and on other high-profile matters, without giving a substantive reason. Her dismissal, echoed in multiple reports, came alongside the firing of other prosecutors and the ethics chief, and amid political pressure over the Epstein files. In Kentucky, DOJ asked for a one-day sentence for Brett Hankison, the former officer convicted of violating Breonna Taylor\'92s civil rights, despite the gravity of the underlying raid. In immigration courts, the administration fired judges even as Congress had just funded more positions, and it appealed a ruling that barred racial profiling in ICE raids. A class-action suit accused DHS and DOJ of colluding to arrest immigrants at courthouse hearings, and another challenged courthouse arrests as unconstitutional. These cases showed resistance. But the pattern of decisions from the top\'97dropping inconvenient prosecutions, seeking leniency for police abuses, reshaping immigration adjudication\'97moved the \'93law as weapon, not limit\'94 trait forward. Law was being used to protect allies, punish enemies, and clear space for executive projects, rather than to stand above them.\
