Policy changes tightened the net further. ICE Director Todd Lyons issued a memo allowing deportations to third countries with as little as six hours\'92 notice, often without assurances against persecution or torture. Another policy made undocumented immigrants ineligible for bond hearings while their deportation cases were pending, shifting release decisions from judges to DHS officials. A Guardian report described the administration\'92s plan to end bond hearings for those who entered without status, backed by a Republican Congress that had just allocated $45 billion to ICE detention over four years. In Oregon, ICE agents broke a car window to arrest Mahdi Khanbabazadeh, a chiropractor married to a U.S. citizen, as he dropped his child at preschool; in another case, an Irish tourist who overstayed his visa by three days due to a medical issue was held for about 100 days in criminal facilities before deportation and a ten-year ban. At \'93Alligator Alcatraz,\'94 more than 250 detainees had no criminal record. These stories were not isolated abuses. They were the human face of a system in which immigrants and refugees occupied a lower tier of rights, with fewer procedural protections and greater exposure to state power.\
