Behind the visible raids, the data infrastructure of enforcement thickened. ProPublica reported that the IRS was developing a system to share confidential tax data, including home addresses, with ICE for deportation targeting, despite earlier legal objections from the agency\'92s own counsel. Separately, the administration struck an agreement to give ICE access to Medicaid data on up to 79 million recipients, including addresses and Social Security numbers, under the stated aim of preventing fraud. Career civil servants had warned of statutory violations, but their concerns were overridden. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act, a tax and spending law, poured more than $6 billion into border surveillance: biometric collection, license plate readers, phone hacking tools, and hundreds of new towers, much of it contracted to firms like Palantir and Anduril. These systems were justified as security measures, but they also entrenched a world in which ordinary people\'97especially the poor, the sick, and the foreign-born\'97were ever more visible to the state, while elite misconduct remained shielded behind secrecy and selective disclosure. The Democracy Clock registered this as a rise in surveillance of citizens and opacity around elite crimes.\
